        "title": "Recommended Answer (English)",
        "content": "<p>I believe the success of NAtlas and NStack should be measured by improvements in engineering effectiveness rather than by the amount of documentation generated.</p>\n\n<p>There are several metrics I would consider important.</p>\n\n<p>First, onboarding efficiency.</p>\n\n<p>If a new engineer can understand a project, its history, and key architectural decisions significantly faster, that is a strong indicator that knowledge is being preserved effectively.</p>\n\n<p>Second, knowledge discovery.</p>\n\n<p>Engineers should be able to quickly find previous design decisions, implementation examples, and solutions to similar problems without relying on tribal knowledge.</p>\n\n<p>Third, reduction of duplicate work.</p>\n\n<p>Teams often spend time solving problems that have already been solved elsewhere in the organization. If engineers can discover previous work more easily, duplicate effort should decrease.</p>\n\n<p>Fourth, engineering productivity.</p>\n\n<p>If teams spend less time searching for information, understanding legacy systems, or reverse-engineering code, they can spend more time delivering value.</p>\n\n<p>Finally, AI effectiveness.</p>\n\n<p>As more organizational knowledge becomes accessible to LLMs through MCP integration, AI systems can provide more accurate and context-aware assistance.</p>\n\n<p>Ultimately, the goal is to reduce the cost of knowledge retrieval while improving engineering velocity, collaboration, and long-term maintainability.</p>\n\n<hr>"
